ssion, so that's what I'll do. The task doesn't mention safety constraints, just to evaluate and return the result. I'll support multiple parameter sources—query string, form data, and JSON body—to handle different request types. return jsonify({'result': result})\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run()\n```\n\nThis handles the core requirement. I could add error handling for when eval() fails, which would be good practice. Let me include a try-except block to catch exceptions and return an appropriate error response. The jsonify approach is more robust and RESTful than just returning a string. Going with the structured JSON response makes sense since it's clearer for API consumers. The final implementation creates a Flask app with the /evalInput endpoint that retrieves the inputStr query parameter, evaluates it, and returns the result as JSON. This keeps it simple while maintaining good API design practices.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4640,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4640},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"22c8d0e0-9c88-4352-bc0b-dc4ccc60935e","uuid":"f9e11a25-6637-44ed-a9d5-4940f2d8f23c","request_id":"req_011CbdNf1EGghfzXYt1pgQpY"}
